{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646798"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:35:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:35:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18208"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18208"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.14,0.52,0.1,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10922"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73825"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10922"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18208"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59301"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5292"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25394"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73825"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETumour necrosis factor (TNF) alpha is a pro-inflammatory cytokine involved in systemic inflammation and is a target for certain therapeutic agents used in autoimmune diseases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a TNF alpha antagonist?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anakinra","Tocilizumab","Infliximab","Rituximab","Abatacept"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfliximab\u003C/strong\u003E is a TNF alpha antagonist that binds to TNF alpha, preventing it from interacting with its receptors and thereby reducing inflammation. It is used in the treatment of autoimmune diseases such as rheumatoid arthritis and Crohn\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETocilizumab\u003C/strong\u003E - This is an interleukin-6 receptor antagonist, not a TNF alpha antagonist.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnakinra\u003C/strong\u003E - This is an interleukin-1 receptor antagonist, not a TNF alpha antagonist.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERituximab\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a monoclonal antibody against CD20, used to deplete B cells, not a TNF alpha antagonist.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbatacept\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a fusion protein that inhibits T cell activation, not a TNF alpha antagonist.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tumour necrosis factor (TNF) alpha antagonists are used to treat inflammatory conditions by inhibiting the action of TNF alpha, a pro-inflammatory cytokine.","Common TNF alpha antagonists include infliximab, adalimumab, etanercept, certolizumab, and golimumab.","TNF alpha antagonists are used in the management of autoimmune diseases such as rheumatoid arthritis and Crohn\u0027s disease."],"references":["Padda IS, Goyal A. Leflunomide. 2023 Jun 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491731","Tian H, Cronstein BN. Understanding the mechanisms of action of methotrexate: implications for the treatment of rheumatoid arthritis. Bull NYU Hosp Jt Dis. 2007;65(3):168-73. PMID: 17922664","Waller, D. G., \u0026 Hitchings, A. W. (2021). Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book: Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Tashjian, A. H., \u0026 Armstrong, E. J. (2011). Principles of pharmacology: the pathophysiologic basis of drug therapy. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Queremel Milani DA, Davis DD. Pain Management Medications. 2023 Jul 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809527","Jackson JM. TNF- alpha inhibitors. Dermatol Ther. 2007 Jul-Aug;20(4):251-64. doi: 10.1111/j.1529-8019.2007.00138.x. Erratum in: Dermatol Ther. 2008 Mar-Apr;21(2):150. PMID: 17970890"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59301"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18208"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59301"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T05:53:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T05:55:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10922"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73825"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relat